There's a device inside
of the box that's

00:11:55.050 --> 00:11:58.680
capable of killing the cat by
breaking open a vial of poison

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:00.060
gas or something.

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:03.510
That device is triggered by
some random event generator like

00:12:03.510 --> 00:12:07.830
a sample of some radioactive
material that either decays,

00:12:07.830 --> 00:12:10.590
producing a bit of
radiation, or doesn't.

00:12:10.590 --> 00:12:11.950
You close the lid.

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:15.050
The cat and the poison gas
and the radioactive sample

00:12:15.050 --> 00:12:16.950
become a sealed system.

00:12:16.950 --> 00:12:19.710
You cannot predict or
know what has happened."

00:12:19.710 --> 00:12:22.260
NICOLE GALLAND: "You don't know
if the cat is alive or dead?"

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:23.850
NEAL STEPHENSON: "It's
not just that you don't.

00:12:23.850 --> 00:12:24.630
You can't.

00:12:24.630 --> 00:12:26.790
There's literally
no way of knowing.

00:12:26.790 --> 00:12:29.130
Now in a classical
physics way of thinking,

00:12:29.130 --> 00:12:30.840
it's either one or the other.

00:12:30.840 --> 00:12:34.230
The cat is either
alive or dead for real.

00:12:34.230 --> 00:12:36.030
You just don't
happen to know which.

00:12:36.030 --> 00:12:37.980
But in a quantum
physics way of thinking,

00:12:37.980 --> 00:12:40.770
the cat really is
both alive and dead.

00:12:40.770 --> 00:12:43.980
It exists in two mutually
incompatible states

00:12:43.980 --> 00:12:45.450
at the same time.

00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:47.460
Not until you open the
lid and look inside

00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:48.836
does the wave
function collapse."

00:12:48.836 --> 00:12:50.001
NICOLE GALLAND: "Whoa, whoa.

00:12:50.001 --> 00:12:51.300
You had me until the very end.

00:12:51.300 --> 00:12:53.137
When did we start
talking about--

00:12:53.137 --> 00:12:53.970
why did you call it?

00:12:53.970 --> 00:12:55.200
A wave function?

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:57.629
And how does that
whatever it is collapse?"

00:12:57.629 --> 00:12:58.670
NEAL STEPHENSON: "My bad.

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:01.810
It's just physicist lingo
for what I was saying.

00:13:01.810 --> 00:13:04.800
If you were to express the
Schrodinger's cat experiment

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:07.330
mathematically, you'd
write down an equation

00:13:07.330 --> 00:13:08.580
that's called a wave function.

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:12.290
That function has multiple
terms that are superimposed.

00:13:12.290 --> 00:13:14.010
It's not just one thing."

00:13:14.010 --> 00:13:15.639
NICOLE GALLAND:
"Multiple terms?"

00:13:15.639 --> 00:13:18.180
NEAL STEPHENSON: "Yeah, a term
here means a fragment of math.

00:13:18.180 --> 00:13:20.465
It is to an equation what
a phrase is to a sentence."

00:13:20.465 --> 00:13:21.840
NICOLE GALLAND:
"So you're saying

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:24.341
there's one term for cat is
alive and another for cat

00:13:24.341 --> 00:13:24.840
is dead.

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:26.850
Is that what you
mean in this usage?"

00:13:26.850 --> 00:13:28.387
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"Yes, o linguist."

00:13:28.387 --> 00:13:30.720
NICOLE GALLAND: "And when you
say they're superimposed?"

00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:31.680
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"Mathematically, it just

00:13:31.680 --> 00:13:33.810
means that they're sort
of added to each other

00:13:33.810 --> 00:13:35.850
to make a combined
picture of the system."

00:13:35.850 --> 00:13:37.980
NICOLE GALLAND: "Until it
collapses or whatever."

00:13:37.980 --> 00:13:39.855
NEAL STEPHENSON: "Multiple
terms superimposed

00:13:39.855 --> 00:13:40.770
is a quantum thing.

00:13:40.770 --> 00:13:42.860
It's the essence of
quantum mechanics,

00:13:42.860 --> 00:13:44.640
but there is this
interesting fact, which

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:47.030
is that that kind
of math only works,

00:13:47.030 --> 00:13:49.950
it only provides an accurate
description of the system

00:13:49.950 --> 00:13:52.260
until you open the
lid and look inside.

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:55.320
At that point, you see a live
cat or a dead cat, period.

00:13:55.320 --> 00:13:57.690
It has become a
classical system"

00:13:57.690 --> 00:14:01.050
NICOLE GALLAND: "Department
of deadly observations?

00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:02.137
He rolled his eyes.

00:14:02.137 --> 00:14:04.470
Anyway, that's what you mean
by the collapse of the wave

00:14:04.470 --> 00:14:05.160
function."

00:14:05.160 --> 00:14:06.290
NEAL STEPHENSON: "Yeah
it's just physicist

00:14:06.290 --> 00:14:07.860
speak for the thing
that happens when

00:14:07.860 --> 00:14:10.740
all of the superimposed
terms, the descriptions

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:13.380
of different possible
realities, resolve

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:15.750
into a single classical
outcome that our brains can

00:14:15.750 --> 00:14:16.500
understand."

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:19.770
NICOLE GALLAND: "Our scientific
rational brains, you mean.

00:14:19.770 --> 00:14:22.110
A look of mild satisfaction
came onto his face."

00:14:22.110 --> 00:14:22.830
NEAL STEPHENSON: "Exactly."

00:14:22.830 --> 00:14:24.940
NICOLE GALLAND: "But now we've
circled back to my theory."

00:14:24.940 --> 00:14:26.070
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"Which theory is that?"

00:14:26.070 --> 00:14:26.880
NICOLE GALLAND: "The
one that belongs

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:28.860
more to children's
literature than to reality.

00:14:28.860 --> 00:14:29.910
Remember?"

00:14:29.910 --> 00:14:30.400
NEAL STEPHENSON: "Oh, yeah.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:31.860
People have to
believe in magic."

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:32.800
NICOLE GALLAND: "Yes."

00:14:32.800 --> 00:14:35.008
NEAL STEPHENSON: "That's
not exactly what I'm saying.

00:14:35.008 --> 00:14:38.130
Yes, human consciousness is
in the loop, but hear me out.

00:14:38.130 --> 00:14:41.070
If you buy the many worlds
interpretation of quantum

00:14:41.070 --> 00:14:43.710
mechanics, it means that all
possible outcomes are really

00:14:43.710 --> 00:14:44.585
happening somewhere."

00:14:44.585 --> 00:14:46.668
NICOLE GALLAND: "There's
one world with a live cat

00:14:46.668 --> 00:14:47.880
and another with a dead cat."

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:48.570
NEAL STEPHENSON: "Exactly.

00:14:48.570 --> 00:14:49.260
No kidding.

00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:52.620
Complete, fully independent
realities that are the same,

00:14:52.620 --> 00:14:55.410
except that in one of them, the
cat's dead, and in the other,

00:14:55.410 --> 00:14:56.070
it's alive.

00:14:56.070 --> 00:14:58.290
In the quantum
superposition, that just

00:14:58.290 --> 00:15:00.210
means that the
scientist standing there

00:15:00.210 --> 00:15:03.330
with his hand on the lid of the
box is at a fork in the road.

00:15:03.330 --> 00:15:06.150
Both paths, both
worlds are open to him.

00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:08.400
He could shunt into
one or the other.

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:11.340
And when he hauls the lid
open, the decision gets made.

00:15:11.340 --> 00:15:12.990
He's now in one
world or the other,

00:15:12.990 --> 00:15:14.250
and there's no going back."

00:15:14.250 --> 00:15:16.950
NICOLE GALLAND: "'OK,' I said,
not in the sense of I agree

00:15:16.950 --> 00:15:19.610
with you, but in the sense
of I am paying attention."

00:15:19.610 --> 00:15:21.484
NEAL STEPHENSON: "The
scientist can't control

00:15:21.484 --> 00:15:23.182
which path he or she takes."

00:15:23.182 --> 00:15:25.140
NICOLE GALLAND: "I saw
that he was trolling me,

00:15:25.140 --> 00:15:27.960
waiting for me to
pick up the bait.

00:15:27.960 --> 00:15:29.280
No, it was more than that.

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:31.140
He wanted me to
mention a possibility

00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:33.960
that he could think about but
never say out loud, because he

00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:35.760
was all Mr. Science.

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:36.960
So I did.

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:38.850
Let's switch it up a
little, then, I said,

00:15:38.850 --> 00:15:42.300
and swap out the white lab
coat and the clipboard for--

00:15:42.300 --> 00:15:44.760
I don't know-- a pointy
black hat and a broom,

00:15:44.760 --> 00:15:48.660
and lose a pronoun, if she
did somehow have the ability

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:50.460
to choose which
world she was going

00:15:50.460 --> 00:15:53.970
to be shunted to when she opened
the lid, if she could control

00:15:53.970 --> 00:15:54.597
the outcome."

00:15:54.597 --> 00:15:56.430
NEAL STEPHENSON: "It
would look like magic."

00:15:56.430 --> 00:15:57.120
NICOLE GALLAND: "What
do you mean look like?

00:15:57.120 --> 00:15:58.350
It would be magic."

00:15:58.350 --> 00:15:59.975
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"Just saying that it's

00:15:59.975 --> 00:16:03.240
about choosing possible
outcomes that already exist,

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:06.480
slipstreaming between closely
related alternate realities

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:08.772
as opposed to bringing those
realities into existence."

00:16:08.772 --> 00:16:10.479
NICOLE GALLAND: "But
that's a distinction

00:16:10.479 --> 00:16:11.520
without a difference."

00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:13.978
NEAL STEPHENSON: "As far as
normal observers are concerned,

00:16:13.978 --> 00:16:16.142
people who haven't studied
quantum physics, sure."

00:16:16.142 --> 00:16:17.850
NICOLE GALLAND: "Put
it however you like.

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:20.190
A witch may summon
the desired effect

00:16:20.190 --> 00:16:23.070
from a parallel/simultaneous
reality.

00:16:23.070 --> 00:16:25.650
Thus, the historical
references of witches' magic

00:16:25.650 --> 00:16:27.550
as summoning-- that
is quite literally

00:16:27.550 --> 00:16:28.860
what they were doing."

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:30.965
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"My hypothesis."

00:16:30.965 --> 00:16:33.090
NICOLE GALLAND: "Tristan
said, pronouncing the word

00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:36.549
with exaggerated care, since
he had a few beers in him."

00:16:36.549 --> 00:16:38.090
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"Is that photography

00:16:38.090 --> 00:16:41.060
disables this summoning,
as you called it.

00:16:41.060 --> 00:16:43.970
Photography breaks
magic by embalming

00:16:43.970 --> 00:16:46.460
a specific moment, one
version of reality,

00:16:46.460 --> 00:16:48.320
into a recorded image.

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:50.630
Once that moment is
so recorded, then

00:16:50.630 --> 00:16:53.000
all other possible
versions of that moment

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.057
are excluded from the world
that contains that photograph."

00:16:56.057 --> 00:16:57.140
NICOLE GALLAND: "I get it.

00:16:57.140 --> 00:17:00.620
There's no wiggle room left in
which to function magically.

00:17:00.620 --> 00:17:01.400
He nodded.

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:04.460
He seemed relieved to have
got all of this off his chest

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:06.930
and that I hadn't laughed
him out of the room.

00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:09.859
'You've been thinking about
this for a while,' I said.

00:17:09.859 --> 00:17:11.300
He nodded.

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:13.220
But it wasn't until we
saw the daguerreotype

00:17:13.220 --> 00:17:15.290
of the solar eclipse
that the penny dropped."

00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:16.819
NEAL STEPHENSON: "That's right."

00:17:16.819 --> 00:17:18.985
NICOLE GALLAND: "That was
only about the bazillionth

00:17:18.985 --> 00:17:20.060
daguerreotype ever made.

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:22.670
People had been taking
photographs for 16 years

00:17:22.670 --> 00:17:23.480
by that point.

00:17:23.480 --> 00:17:25.190
What's so special
about that one?"

00:17:25.190 --> 00:17:26.606
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"The scope of it,

00:17:26.606 --> 00:17:30.260
I think, the number of
minds and worlds affected.

00:17:30.260 --> 00:17:33.890
If I'm Louis Daguerre screwing
around in my lab in Paris,

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:36.080
taking pictures of
whatever's handy,

00:17:36.080 --> 00:17:38.090
then I'd collapse
the waveform, yes,

00:17:38.090 --> 00:17:40.670
but only in as much as
it encompasses my brain

00:17:40.670 --> 00:17:42.980
and a few little
objects in my lab.

00:17:42.980 --> 00:17:46.310
If I showed the daguerreotype
to my wife or my friend,

00:17:46.310 --> 00:17:49.500
then the effect spreads
to them as well,

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:51.950
and we can guess that witches
who live in the neighborhood

00:17:51.950 --> 00:17:54.980
might sense a dampening
of their magical abilities

00:17:54.980 --> 00:17:56.540
without understanding why.

00:17:56.540 --> 00:18:00.590
But the total eclipse of
the sun on July 28, 1851,

00:18:00.590 --> 00:18:03.530
was probably witnessed
by more human beings

00:18:03.530 --> 00:18:06.230
than any other event in
the history of the world up

00:18:06.230 --> 00:18:06.890
to that point."

00:18:06.890 --> 00:18:07.490
NICOLE GALLAND: "Of course.

00:18:07.490 --> 00:18:09.050
Everyone in Europe
could see it."

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:10.550
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"Just by looking up

00:18:10.550 --> 00:18:13.210
into the sky, hundreds of
millions of people, Mel.

00:18:13.210 --> 00:18:16.010
That event captured more
eyeballs at the same moment

00:18:16.010 --> 00:18:18.530
than any Beyonce
video on YouTube,

00:18:18.530 --> 00:18:21.230
and to the extent that
it was frozen and bombed

00:18:21.230 --> 00:18:22.610
on a daguerreotype, well--"

00:18:22.610 --> 00:18:24.609
NICOLE GALLAND: "If
previous uses of photography

00:18:24.609 --> 00:18:27.320
had dampened magic, then this
was like dumping the Atlantic

00:18:27.320 --> 00:18:28.250
Ocean on it."

00:18:28.250 --> 00:18:29.666
NEAL STEPHENSON:
"When the shutter

00:18:29.666 --> 00:18:32.570
opened to capture that first
perfect image of the eclipse,

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:36.472
magic ceased to function
across all human societies."

00:18:36.472 --> 00:18:38.930
NICOLE GALLAND: "We back checked
the dates of all documents

00:18:38.930 --> 00:18:40.250
from 1851.

00:18:40.250 --> 00:18:43.250
Indeed, there were three from
the first half of the year, two

00:18:43.250 --> 00:18:44.630
English, one Italian.

00:18:44.630 --> 00:18:47.990
There was a fragment of one
in late July, Hungarian.

00:18:47.990 --> 00:18:51.802
There were none after July 28th,
the date of the eclipse, none."

00:18:51.802 --> 00:18:53.010
NEAL STEPHENSON: "That said."

00:18:53.010 --> 00:18:54.968
NICOLE GALLAND: "Muttered
Tristan, preoccupied,

00:18:54.968 --> 00:18:55.830
getting to his feet.

00:18:55.830 --> 00:18:58.160
He rested his hands on his
desk and stared absently

00:18:58.160 --> 00:18:59.510
at the wall.

00:18:59.510 --> 00:19:01.280
'Yes,' I said.

00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:02.240
I felt deflated.

00:19:02.240 --> 00:19:04.160
Although he'd never
told me why D.O.D.O. was

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:06.390
so interested in
understanding magic,

00:19:06.390 --> 00:19:08.270
common sense screamed
it was because they

00:19:08.270 --> 00:19:10.550
wanted to be able to do it.

00:19:10.550 --> 00:19:13.280
Department of Doing the Occult?

00:19:13.280 --> 00:19:14.877
Which clearly
could never happen.

00:19:14.877 --> 00:19:16.460
There's no getting
rid of photography,

00:19:16.460 --> 00:19:19.010
so there's no
bringing magic back.

00:19:19.010 --> 00:19:20.840
Tristan froze, and
after a beat, jerked

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:22.689
his head in my direction."

00:19:22.689 --> 00:19:23.980
NEAL STEPHENSON: "You're right.

00:19:23.980 --> 00:19:24.740
That's it.

00:19:24.740 --> 00:19:28.560
Where there is no photography,
there could still be magic."

00:19:28.560 --> 00:19:30.710
NICOLE GALLAND: "That's
not quite what I said.

00:19:30.710 --> 00:19:32.364
He began to pace the office.

00:19:32.364 --> 00:19:34.280
We had made it somewhat
larger by knocking out

00:19:34.280 --> 00:19:36.890
walls that separated it
from adjoining spaces,

00:19:36.890 --> 00:19:38.420
but this still
required following

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:41.750
a figure 8-ish path between
piles of books, artifacts,

00:19:41.750 --> 00:19:44.000
freestanding gun
safes to be recycled,

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:45.830
beer bottles, and
still unexplained high

00:19:45.830 --> 00:19:47.360
tech military gear."

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:50.120
NEAL STEPHENSON: "How do
we get rid of photography?"

00:19:50.120 --> 00:19:52.362
NICOLE GALLAND: "We cannot
get rid of photography."

00:19:52.362 --> 00:19:54.320
NEAL STEPHENSON: "No,
it's definitely possible.

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:56.360
I just have to figure
out how it's done."

00:19:56.360 --> 00:19:58.010
NICOLE GALLAND: "What do
you mean how it's done?"

00:19:58.010 --> 00:19:59.801
NEAL STEPHENSON: "I'm
not seeing something.

00:19:59.801 --> 00:20:01.010
What am I missing?"

00:20:01.010 --> 00:20:02.030
NICOLE GALLAND: "You're
missing the part where

00:20:02.030 --> 00:20:04.280
photography became
ubiquitous, and all magic

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:06.980
went away forever.

00:20:06.980 --> 00:20:09.740
He turned to look at me, his
eyes focused now and bright."

00:20:09.740 --> 00:20:11.907
NEAL STEPHENSON: "No,
it's not a lost cause."

00:20:11.907 --> 00:20:13.490
NICOLE GALLAND: "That
was not the tone

00:20:13.490 --> 00:20:15.500
of hypothesis or theory.

00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:18.410
That was the tone of
either faith or knowledge.

00:20:18.410 --> 00:20:21.620
I felt a shiver
run down my spine.

00:20:21.620 --> 00:20:24.530
I realized there are a lot
of things you can't tell me,

00:20:24.530 --> 00:20:26.720
but whatever it
specifically is you're not

00:20:26.720 --> 00:20:29.930
telling me at this precise
moment, fucking tell me.

00:20:29.930 --> 00:20:32.060
Otherwise, I'm useless.

00:20:32.060 --> 00:20:33.920
His gaze went fuzzy
again as he engaged

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:35.960
in some brief mental soliloquy.

00:20:35.960 --> 00:20:36.944
Then he nodded."

00:20:36.944 --> 00:20:38.610
NEAL STEPHENSON: "I
can't tell you much.

00:20:38.610 --> 00:20:41.915
But I can tell you that
we know it's possible."

00:20:41.915 --> 00:20:42.790
NICOLE GALLAND: "We?"

00:20:42.790 --> 00:20:45.620
NEAL STEPHENSON: "D.O.D.O.
There's evidence.

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:48.483
That's all I can say."

00:20:48.483 --> 00:20:49.274
NICOLE GALLAND: OK.

00:20:49.274 --> 00:20:51.357
NEAL STEPHENSON: So that's
the end of the reading.

00:20:51.357 --> 00:20:53.060
[APPLAUSE]

00:20:53.060 --> 00:20:56.050
Thanks.

00:20:56.050 --> 00:20:58.470
So that's kind of the
setup for the story.

00:20:58.470 --> 00:20:59.820
That's all the first 30 or so--

00:20:59.820 --> 00:21:01.820
NICOLE GALLAND: And then
there's still all that.

00:21:01.820 --> 00:21:02.810
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah.

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:03.900
Yeah.

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:06.970
So this is the point where
we normally jump over

00:21:06.970 --> 00:21:08.640
to question and answer time.

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:12.540
So I believe we have some
kind of bouncing cube

00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:16.560
that is going to be
used to facilitate that.

00:21:16.560 --> 00:21:19.170
Thanks for turning
up the lights.

00:21:19.170 --> 00:21:22.770
Well, it is quite a sort
of empty band in the middle

00:21:22.770 --> 00:21:23.580
of the room there.

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:25.455
We've definitely got
back of the bus people--

00:21:25.455 --> 00:21:27.246
NICOLE GALLAND: If this
was a folk concert,

00:21:27.246 --> 00:21:29.600
we would encourage you all
to move down to the front.

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:33.200
NEAL STEPHENSON: Fortunately,
it's not a folk--

00:21:33.200 --> 00:21:34.885
yeah.

00:21:34.885 --> 00:21:36.510
SPEAKER: So we have
this throwable mic,

00:21:36.510 --> 00:21:38.009
which you've probably
seen if you've

00:21:38.009 --> 00:21:40.440
been to any of these events
in the last month or so.

00:21:40.440 --> 00:21:41.280
So does anyone have a question?

00:21:41.280 --> 00:21:42.571
NICOLE GALLAND: That's so cool.

00:21:45.075 --> 00:21:46.450
AUDIENCE: So now
I know, I guess,

00:21:46.450 --> 00:21:50.170
why Google sold off
our satellite business.

00:21:50.170 --> 00:21:52.720
[INAUDIBLE] next, I guess.

00:21:52.720 --> 00:21:55.660
So how do you guys collaborate
on a book like this?

00:21:55.660 --> 00:21:58.150
Did you work together, or
did you do it remotely?

00:21:58.150 --> 00:21:59.690
Did you do a chapter at a time?

00:21:59.690 --> 00:22:01.840
NEAL STEPHENSON:
So we keep saying

00:22:01.840 --> 00:22:05.230
that we need to fabricate a
bunch of stories about all

00:22:05.230 --> 00:22:08.800
the drama and tension
that existed and made it

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:11.830
such a thrill-charged
collaboration.

00:22:11.830 --> 00:22:15.880
But it was pretty
calm, professional.

00:22:15.880 --> 00:22:19.840
There was the idea, which came
from an idea I came up with,

00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:21.554
and we developed it
to a certain point,

00:22:21.554 --> 00:22:23.470
where we kind of knew
who the characters were.

00:22:23.470 --> 00:22:25.940
We had a sense of what
kind of people they were

00:22:25.940 --> 00:22:28.060
and the overall
arc of the story.

00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:33.097
And then Nikki kind of would
break trail, for the most part.

00:22:33.097 --> 00:22:34.930
NICOLE GALLAND: I would
play around with it,

00:22:34.930 --> 00:22:37.430
and then when I felt like I had
gotten it as far as I could,

00:22:37.430 --> 00:22:38.530
I'd pass it back to Neal.

00:22:38.530 --> 00:22:39.934
Neal would tweak it.

00:22:39.934 --> 00:22:41.350
There were some
things, especially

00:22:41.350 --> 00:22:42.891
like the section
you just read, which

00:22:42.891 --> 00:22:44.860
there's a lot of
quantum theory there,

00:22:44.860 --> 00:22:47.020
which Neal's a little more
comfortable than I am.

00:22:47.020 --> 00:22:51.020
So he broke ground on
those parts of that

00:22:51.020 --> 00:22:52.250
and then would send it to me.

00:22:52.250 --> 00:22:54.170
So it really was-- it
was very intuitive.

00:22:54.170 --> 00:22:56.830
It just seemed very
obvious to both of us

00:22:56.830 --> 00:23:01.360
who was better prepared in
terms of schedule and expertise

00:23:01.360 --> 00:23:04.210
or even just the kind of
voice we were creating.

00:23:04.210 --> 00:23:07.939
So whoever it made sense
to start would start,

00:23:07.939 --> 00:23:09.730
and then the other
person would do pick up.

00:23:09.730 --> 00:23:11.230
So we both ended up--

00:23:11.230 --> 00:23:13.789
our fingerprints are all
over the whole thing,

00:23:13.789 --> 00:23:14.830
both of our fingerprints.

00:23:14.830 --> 00:23:17.682
But it was really--
it was very intuitive.

00:23:17.682 --> 00:23:18.640
Actually, that's a lie.

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:20.080
He kept me locked
in his basement

00:23:20.080 --> 00:23:23.472
and fed me chocolate whenever
I finished a chapter.

00:23:23.472 --> 00:23:25.180
NEAL STEPHENSON: It's
an epistolary book,

00:23:25.180 --> 00:23:31.480
so it's written as a series of
documents that were allegedly

00:23:31.480 --> 00:23:33.280
extracted from an
archive that was

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:35.150
stolen from this organization.

00:23:35.150 --> 00:23:39.730
So what you've been hearing
is a little bit anomalous

00:23:39.730 --> 00:23:43.100
in that it's an extended
narrative written by one voice.

00:23:43.100 --> 00:23:45.400
But there's big sections
of the book that

00:23:45.400 --> 00:23:49.390
are in the form of text message
exchanges or transcripts

00:23:49.390 --> 00:23:54.460
or email threads or Slack
messages or PowerPoint

00:23:54.460 --> 00:23:55.480
presentations.

00:23:55.480 --> 00:23:59.290
Kind of the whole bureaucratic
communication apparatus

00:23:59.290 --> 00:24:04.580
ends up making an
appearance in this book.

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:05.246
AUDIENCE: Hello?

00:24:05.246 --> 00:24:07.110
Oh.

00:24:07.110 --> 00:24:08.840
Besides the how, why?

00:24:08.840 --> 00:24:09.340
Why?

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:11.010
What made the two
of you think this

00:24:11.010 --> 00:24:14.230
was a book that really needed
somebody else's voice, somebody

00:24:14.230 --> 00:24:16.624
else's input?

00:24:16.624 --> 00:24:18.790
NEAL STEPHENSON: Well, we
worked together previously

00:24:18.790 --> 00:24:25.360
on another big collaborative
project called "The Mongoliad,"

00:24:25.360 --> 00:24:29.560
so we kind of had a
sense that it could work.

00:24:29.560 --> 00:24:32.956
And this just--

00:24:32.956 --> 00:24:36.557
I mean the original idea kind
of came to me as I said--

00:24:36.557 --> 00:24:38.140
as I started thinking
about what would

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:41.050
be entailed in actually
making it into a novel.

00:24:41.050 --> 00:24:44.860
And it just seemed to me like a
completely obvious opportunity

00:24:44.860 --> 00:24:50.110
to collaborate with Nikki
again, since her metier is

00:24:50.110 --> 00:24:56.817
writing well-researched
historical novels.

00:24:56.817 --> 00:24:58.900
NICOLE GALLAND: He twisted
my arm, and I said yes.

00:24:58.900 --> 00:25:02.772
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:04.710 --> 00:25:06.670
AUDIENCE: So I don't want
to give any spoilers,

00:25:06.670 --> 00:25:10.980
but I'm seeing some relationship
to "Anathem" in this.

00:25:10.980 --> 00:25:13.476
I won't say what.

00:25:13.476 --> 00:25:14.850
Without giving it
away, should we

00:25:14.850 --> 00:25:18.100
be keeping our eye open
for any Easter eggs?

00:25:18.100 --> 00:25:20.100
NEAL STEPHENSON: No,
there's none of that stuff.

00:25:20.100 --> 00:25:22.650
But you're correct
about the connection.

00:25:22.650 --> 00:25:27.070
So when I was
working on "Anathem,"

00:25:27.070 --> 00:25:31.770
I got interested in this whole
many worlds interpretation

00:25:31.770 --> 00:25:34.890
of quantum mechanics
and learned that there's

00:25:34.890 --> 00:25:37.650
a branch of metaphysics,
so there are still

00:25:37.650 --> 00:25:41.260
people who do metaphysics
for a living, it turns out.

00:25:41.260 --> 00:25:43.770
And some of them think
about alternate worlds

00:25:43.770 --> 00:25:46.350
or possible worlds
in a very serious way

00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:55.200
like with logical formalism,
and so it's a thing.

00:25:55.200 --> 00:25:57.930
And it stuck with
me a little bit,

00:25:57.930 --> 00:26:02.400
and so I think you're right in
seeing that kind of connection.

00:26:02.400 --> 00:26:05.130
But there's not the
other kind of connection

00:26:05.130 --> 00:26:06.131
that you're thinking of.

00:26:06.131 --> 00:26:07.796
NICOLE GALLAND: I
have a little anecdote

00:26:07.796 --> 00:26:09.930
I can add to that, which
is the first two times--

00:26:09.930 --> 00:26:12.210
you're not the first person
that's pointed that out--

00:26:12.210 --> 00:26:15.060
but the first two times,
someone in the audience

00:26:15.060 --> 00:26:19.290
asked Neal about that, like
it hadn't occurred to him.

00:26:19.290 --> 00:26:21.300
It's occurred to him
now, because he's been

00:26:21.300 --> 00:26:22.800
reminded of it enough times.

00:26:25.027 --> 00:26:26.110
NEAL STEPHENSON: Oh, good.

00:26:26.110 --> 00:26:28.450
It finally went airborne.

00:26:28.450 --> 00:26:28.950
Just--

00:26:32.320 --> 00:26:34.480
AUDIENCE: Keeping to
the theme of connections

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:38.710
on to earlier books,
any chance Enoch Root

00:26:38.710 --> 00:26:41.320
is walking around
in 1851 in London?

00:26:41.320 --> 00:26:43.600
And if not, any chance
we'll get the final third

00:26:43.600 --> 00:26:46.750
of "Cryptonomicon?"

00:26:46.750 --> 00:26:48.250
NEAL STEPHENSON: Nope.

00:26:48.250 --> 00:26:53.800
I mean it is not connected
to my other books.

00:26:53.800 --> 00:26:56.770
There's no Enoch
Root in this one.

00:26:56.770 --> 00:27:02.500
And no, it's a standalone.

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:06.010
I mean there may be--
there already are

00:27:06.010 --> 00:27:11.080
other spin-outs of this book.

00:27:11.080 --> 00:27:17.570
So we struck up a relationship
with a startup called Bound.

00:27:17.570 --> 00:27:23.950
It's getbound.io, which they're
making an app for reading,

00:27:23.950 --> 00:27:31.690
for enjoying fiction either by
reading it or listening to it.

00:27:31.690 --> 00:27:34.160
And they're sort of coming
out of a gaming background.

00:27:34.160 --> 00:27:35.826
So I think they were
originally thinking

00:27:35.826 --> 00:27:38.880
of adding narrative
content to game worlds,

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:41.860
but it was a really good fit
for what we wanted to do.

00:27:41.860 --> 00:27:45.090
And so they launched on Tuesday.

00:27:45.090 --> 00:27:49.090
They're on the App Store.

00:27:49.090 --> 00:27:51.380
I don't know if they've
got an Android app.

00:27:51.380 --> 00:27:57.190
Anyway, the point is that there
are some other writers who've

00:27:57.190 --> 00:28:00.970
been playing in this world
already during the last year

00:28:00.970 --> 00:28:05.730
or so, and so Bound is going
to be episodically releasing

00:28:05.730 --> 00:28:10.600
some of their work, which
purports to be other leaked

00:28:10.600 --> 00:28:13.210
material from the same archive.

00:28:13.210 --> 00:28:15.969
But it's different characters
and different stories.

00:28:15.969 --> 00:28:17.760
NICOLE GALLAND: Different
narratives, yeah.

00:28:17.760 --> 00:28:19.218
NEAL STEPHENSON:
But no Enoch Root.

00:28:19.218 --> 00:28:21.160
NICOLE GALLAND: And also
different documents.

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:26.780
Are the bureaucratic
documents going into Bound's--

00:28:26.780 --> 00:28:30.170
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah, the
sexual harassment policy is up,

00:28:30.170 --> 00:28:32.280
I think.

00:28:32.280 --> 00:28:37.397
A bunch of the sort of
bureaucratic type things are.

00:28:37.397 --> 00:28:38.980
NICOLE GALLAND: So
I did some of that,

00:28:38.980 --> 00:28:40.810
and then we had six
other writers contribute.

00:28:40.810 --> 00:28:41.920
So there's a whole lot of--

00:28:41.920 --> 00:28:44.294
literally a lot of different
voices involved in that one.

00:28:44.294 --> 00:28:47.710
And it's expanding
gradually through time.

00:28:50.370 --> 00:28:51.870
NEAL STEPHENSON:
I'll heave it back.

00:28:51.870 --> 00:28:54.250
Someone will catch it.

00:28:54.250 --> 00:28:55.880
No?

00:28:55.880 --> 00:28:57.040
No, I guess if they were--

00:28:59.231 --> 00:29:00.730
AUDIENCE: Stylistically,
how did you

00:29:00.730 --> 00:29:03.200
choose to do
bureaucratic documents?

00:29:03.200 --> 00:29:04.449
That's not--

00:29:04.449 --> 00:29:05.740
NEAL STEPHENSON: Really boring.

00:29:05.740 --> 00:29:07.660
AUDIENCE: --a
traditional novel style.

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:11.422
NEAL STEPHENSON:
Well, you've got to--

00:29:11.422 --> 00:29:16.210
I mean so as I
think you can sense,

00:29:16.210 --> 00:29:19.060
the overall tone of this
book is more lighthearted

00:29:19.060 --> 00:29:20.625
satirical fun--

00:29:20.625 --> 00:29:22.250
NICOLE GALLAND: Than,
say, "Seveneves."

00:29:22.250 --> 00:29:24.700
NEAL STEPHENSON: Right, yeah.

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:33.730
So it's an opportunity to kind
of make fun of that stuff.

00:29:33.730 --> 00:29:37.870
So hopefully, in those
parts of the document that

00:29:37.870 --> 00:29:40.310
are like PowerPoint
presentations,

00:29:40.310 --> 00:29:42.820
they're sufficiently
over the top

00:29:42.820 --> 00:29:47.812
that they'll actually
be enjoyable to read.

00:29:47.812 --> 00:29:50.020
NICOLE GALLAND: Neal did a
lot of the original drafts

00:29:50.020 --> 00:29:53.140
of those, and when I got them,
I was laughing out loud, which

00:29:53.140 --> 00:29:55.300
normally doesn't happen
when I'm reading PowerPoint

00:29:55.300 --> 00:29:56.596
presentations.

00:30:02.015 --> 00:30:03.390
NEAL STEPHENSON:
In front of you.

00:30:03.390 --> 00:30:06.020
NICOLE GALLAND: Throw
that man a cube.

00:30:06.020 --> 00:30:08.150
AUDIENCE: So I think you
tried something similar

00:30:08.150 --> 00:30:09.690
with "Seveneves,"
where "Seveneves"

00:30:09.690 --> 00:30:12.660
was sort of an anchor in
a universe around which

00:30:12.660 --> 00:30:16.070
ancillary projects
were scattered.

00:30:16.070 --> 00:30:17.747
Is that working out well?

00:30:17.747 --> 00:30:19.830
You're doing the same thing
again, so I assume so.

00:30:21.800 --> 00:30:23.300
NEAL STEPHENSON:
I'm trying to think

00:30:23.300 --> 00:30:29.330
of the ancillary
"Seveneves" projects.

00:30:34.010 --> 00:30:37.636
I mean I'm always
thinking about it.

00:30:37.636 --> 00:30:41.860
It seems like something
that ought to work.

00:30:41.860 --> 00:30:45.500
And I feel like I'm in a good,
relatively privileged position

00:30:45.500 --> 00:30:48.215
to be able to try to make
that kind of thing work.

00:30:48.215 --> 00:30:50.436
But then it always turns
out to be really hard,

00:30:50.436 --> 00:30:52.310
and writing novels and
getting them published

00:30:52.310 --> 00:30:54.620
turns out to be really easy.

00:30:54.620 --> 00:30:58.670
So in the case of "Seveneves,"
there is a film adaptation

00:30:58.670 --> 00:31:01.520
under way, and that
seems to be moving along

00:31:01.520 --> 00:31:02.600
in a promising way.

00:31:02.600 --> 00:31:09.020
But what tends to happen is
that if something like that

00:31:09.020 --> 00:31:12.730
gets going, it has a
suppressing effect on everything

00:31:12.730 --> 00:31:18.580
else, because why bother
trying to work on anything

00:31:18.580 --> 00:31:21.510
else like a game
or what have you

00:31:21.510 --> 00:31:24.070
if there's a
possibility that a movie

00:31:24.070 --> 00:31:25.630
project is going to happen?

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:29.440
So it causes everything
else to be sort of abandoned

00:31:29.440 --> 00:31:34.570
or put on hold while you wait
for the next thing to move.

00:31:34.570 --> 00:31:38.990
In the case of the
Bound collaboration,

00:31:38.990 --> 00:31:43.600
so far, that's not happening,
because the timing just

00:31:43.600 --> 00:31:47.080
happened to work out really
well that they had a startup.

00:31:47.080 --> 00:31:50.380
They wanted to launch their
app at exactly the same time

00:31:50.380 --> 00:31:52.330
as the book was going to launch.

00:31:52.330 --> 00:31:56.230
And so it's out there.

00:31:56.230 --> 00:31:58.390
We'll see how it develops.

00:32:06.027 --> 00:32:08.360
NICOLE GALLAND: Can you just
like throw it up in the air

00:32:08.360 --> 00:32:09.754
so we can have--

00:32:09.754 --> 00:32:10.670
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah.

00:32:10.670 --> 00:32:12.860
We were told there was
going to be a flying cube.

00:32:12.860 --> 00:32:13.542
OK.

00:32:13.542 --> 00:32:14.157
Well.

00:32:14.157 --> 00:32:15.240
NICOLE GALLAND: Thank you.

00:32:15.240 --> 00:32:17.210
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah, thanks.

00:32:17.210 --> 00:32:19.340
AUDIENCE: So what's
the best book

00:32:19.340 --> 00:32:22.189
you've read in the last year
that's not one of your own?

00:32:22.189 --> 00:32:23.480
NEAL STEPHENSON: The last year.

00:32:23.480 --> 00:32:25.355
NICOLE GALLAND: Oh, this
is one of those deer

00:32:25.355 --> 00:32:26.585
in headlight questions.

00:32:26.585 --> 00:32:27.710
AUDIENCE: I mean, whatever.

00:32:27.710 --> 00:32:30.370
A book that you read in the
last year that you really liked.

00:32:30.370 --> 00:32:31.917
Doesn't have to be the best.

00:32:31.917 --> 00:32:34.250
NEAL STEPHENSON: No, it's
just this comes up every time,

00:32:34.250 --> 00:32:37.220
and every time, we
say we really should

00:32:37.220 --> 00:32:41.120
have a prepped answer for this.

00:32:41.120 --> 00:32:41.990
And then--

00:32:41.990 --> 00:32:44.090
AUDIENCE: Better than
watching [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:44.090 --> 00:32:46.820
NEAL STEPHENSON: It's terrible,
because it's an opportunity

00:32:46.820 --> 00:32:50.820
to support somebody else's work.

00:32:50.820 --> 00:32:54.380
And-- oh, see, I
finally thought of one.

00:32:54.380 --> 00:33:00.185
Annalee Newitz has
one that's coming out.

00:33:00.185 --> 00:33:03.000
I can't remember
the title of it.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.490
That's terrible.

00:33:05.490 --> 00:33:09.570
But if only there was
some kind of search engine

00:33:09.570 --> 00:33:10.445
that could find this.

00:33:10.445 --> 00:33:11.695
NICOLE GALLAND: In your brain?

00:33:11.695 --> 00:33:12.940
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah.

00:33:12.940 --> 00:33:14.190
NICOLE GALLAND: There will be.

00:33:14.190 --> 00:33:16.950
NEAL STEPHENSON: So Newitz,
N-E-W-I-T-Z, first name,

00:33:16.950 --> 00:33:24.210
Annalee, A-N-N-A-L-E-E.
And I think it's just out,

00:33:24.210 --> 00:33:27.420
so so that's worth checking out.

00:33:27.420 --> 00:33:32.880
It's her first book, so
should be easy to find on Bing

00:33:32.880 --> 00:33:34.442
or whatever.

00:33:34.442 --> 00:33:36.900
NICOLE GALLAND: I know what
the most interesting thing I've

00:33:36.900 --> 00:33:38.910
read in the last year
is, but I guarantee you

00:33:38.910 --> 00:33:41.150
it will not be of
interest to any of you.

00:33:41.150 --> 00:33:43.770
So it's the town
report for the Town

00:33:43.770 --> 00:33:46.530
of West Tisbury,
Massachusetts, which

00:33:46.530 --> 00:33:49.020
is research for a project
I'm working on now.

00:33:49.020 --> 00:33:50.537
And it's really like--

00:33:50.537 --> 00:33:52.620
AUDIENCE: OK, so why was
that so interesting then?

00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:53.786
NICOLE GALLAND: Sorry, what?

00:33:53.786 --> 00:33:57.380
AUDIENCE: Why was that the most
interesting thing you read?

00:33:57.380 --> 00:33:58.910
NICOLE GALLAND: Because it--

00:33:58.910 --> 00:34:01.940
because it fed research
that I was trying to do,

00:34:01.940 --> 00:34:02.850
and it forced me--

00:34:02.850 --> 00:34:04.670
I grew up in the
town of West Tisbury,

00:34:04.670 --> 00:34:08.929
and it forced me to step back
and look at my own microcosm

00:34:08.929 --> 00:34:11.840
as a thing that could be studied
as opposed to just a place

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:14.969
to live in.

00:34:14.969 --> 00:34:17.909
But it made me bend
my brain in a new way.

00:34:17.909 --> 00:34:20.263
But A, I'm almost
the only person

00:34:20.263 --> 00:34:21.679
that it would have
that effect on.

00:34:21.679 --> 00:34:25.449
And you guys have probably never
even heard of West Tisbury, so.

00:34:28.669 --> 00:34:30.627
AUDIENCE: What year
is the report from?

00:34:30.627 --> 00:34:32.460
NEAL STEPHENSON: They're
going to go get it.

