00:35:13.680 --> 00:35:15.530
So that's worth checking out.

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:19.950
You can say that you read
the book before it was on TV.

00:35:19.950 --> 00:35:23.990
AUDIENCE: Is the Annalee
Newitz book, "Autonomous?"

00:35:23.990 --> 00:35:25.820
NEAL STEPHENSON:
That sounds right.

00:35:25.820 --> 00:35:29.210
Part of my problem is that
they send these things to me

00:35:29.210 --> 00:35:32.155
to blurb, and sometimes
they have different titles.

00:35:32.155 --> 00:35:32.780
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:35:32.780 --> 00:35:34.319
NEAL STEPHENSON:
So like I blurbed--

00:35:34.319 --> 00:35:35.360
that's another good one--

00:35:35.360 --> 00:35:39.374
Cory Doctorow's book, which
is now called "Walkaway."

00:35:39.374 --> 00:35:41.165
When I blurbed it, it
was called, "Utopia."

00:35:43.770 --> 00:35:44.580
So.

00:35:44.580 --> 00:35:49.160
And there's one coming
out in September

00:35:49.160 --> 00:35:54.020
by Joe Brassey, who's one of
the other "Mongoliad" writers

00:35:54.020 --> 00:35:59.180
called "Skyfarer," which is just
a great, fun adventure sci-fi

00:35:59.180 --> 00:36:02.114
fantasy novel, so.

00:36:02.114 --> 00:36:03.530
NICOLE GALLAND:
You've been better

00:36:03.530 --> 00:36:05.000
at reading new stuff than me.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:08.570
I'm like in hermit
mode at the moment.

00:36:11.450 --> 00:36:12.462
NEAL STEPHENSON: Nice.

00:36:12.462 --> 00:36:13.670
AUDIENCE: That made me think.

00:36:13.670 --> 00:36:19.370
What genres do you both read
for both inspiration and fun?

00:36:19.370 --> 00:36:21.770
NICOLE GALLAND: I
read a huge range.

00:36:21.770 --> 00:36:26.210
When I'm working on a story
with a particular tone,

00:36:26.210 --> 00:36:29.300
I often try to stay
close to other books that

00:36:29.300 --> 00:36:31.280
are in that tone just
so that my inner voice--

00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:34.430
I tend to walk around thinking
in the voice of whatever I'm

00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:35.180
reading.

00:36:35.180 --> 00:36:38.812
So I try to keep the
voice fairly consistent

00:36:38.812 --> 00:36:40.520
when I'm in a certain
part of my process.

00:36:40.520 --> 00:36:44.080
But then when I'm not, I like to
go as far afield as I possibly

00:36:44.080 --> 00:36:44.580
can.

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:49.700
So historical-- I love
historical fiction.

00:36:49.700 --> 00:36:52.740
I like some sci-fi and fantasy.

00:36:52.740 --> 00:36:55.320
I don't gobble it up
in quite the same way.

00:36:55.320 --> 00:36:57.140
I like contemporary
literary fiction

00:36:57.140 --> 00:36:59.640
and contemporary
commercial fiction,

00:36:59.640 --> 00:37:03.230
and I love kids' books.

00:37:03.230 --> 00:37:06.570
I just like being reminded
of being in that headspace.

00:37:06.570 --> 00:37:09.879
NEAL STEPHENSON: I
read a lot of history.

00:37:09.879 --> 00:37:10.670
Surprise, surprise.

00:37:13.770 --> 00:37:16.880
And some books about science.

00:37:16.880 --> 00:37:20.930
Oh, see, now it's coming to me.

00:37:20.930 --> 00:37:26.330
"Arrival of the Fittest"
by Andreas Wagner--

00:37:26.330 --> 00:37:28.540
really interesting
book about science.

00:37:28.540 --> 00:37:34.190
And it's about
the problem with--

00:37:34.190 --> 00:37:42.590
how does evolution actually
work on a combinatorial level?

00:37:42.590 --> 00:37:45.020
Just randomly
shuffling amino acids

00:37:45.020 --> 00:37:47.450
around doesn't seem like
it would get you anywhere,

00:37:47.450 --> 00:37:53.010
if you look at all of the
combinations that would fail.

00:37:53.010 --> 00:37:54.920
So he's coming at--

00:37:54.920 --> 00:37:56.930
he's at the Santa Fe Institute.

00:37:56.930 --> 00:38:00.020
He's done all kinds of really
interesting computational work

00:38:00.020 --> 00:38:03.080
in this area and has got
a really readable book

00:38:03.080 --> 00:38:08.785
out on that topic that was
pretty amazing to read.

00:38:08.785 --> 00:38:09.660
NICOLE GALLAND: Cool.

00:38:09.660 --> 00:38:10.630
I read a lot of plays.

00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:12.660
I completely forgot that,
because my background

00:38:12.660 --> 00:38:14.290
is in theater,
and I can't really

00:38:14.290 --> 00:38:15.590
divorce myself from that.

00:38:15.590 --> 00:38:19.750
That's-- yeah.

00:38:19.750 --> 00:38:21.660
NEAL STEPHENSON: Anyone else?

00:38:21.660 --> 00:38:22.363
Whoops.

00:38:22.363 --> 00:38:22.796
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:22.796 --> 00:38:23.796
NEAL STEPHENSON: Oh, OK.

00:38:23.796 --> 00:38:24.300
Yeah.

00:38:24.300 --> 00:38:25.484
Thank you.

00:38:25.484 --> 00:38:27.150
NICOLE GALLAND: Taking
one for the team.

00:38:27.150 --> 00:38:29.149
NEAL STEPHENSON: I want
to see a perfect spiral.

00:38:32.530 --> 00:38:34.894
NICOLE GALLAND: Yeah, all right.

00:38:34.894 --> 00:38:36.395
NEAL STEPHENSON:
Now we're talking.

00:38:36.395 --> 00:38:38.520
AUDIENCE: All right, so
this was not the first book

00:38:38.520 --> 00:38:39.561
either of you've written.

00:38:39.561 --> 00:38:42.390
I assume it won't be the
last either of you write.

00:38:42.390 --> 00:38:45.000
I'm just curious, what are
you looking forward to trying

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.649
differently next time, perhaps?

00:38:47.649 --> 00:38:49.690
NEAL STEPHENSON: What are
our next book projects?

00:38:49.690 --> 00:38:52.450
AUDIENCE: Just not necessarily
what the plot is, but just

00:38:52.450 --> 00:38:54.720
what are you going to try
doing differently as you

00:38:54.720 --> 00:38:56.010
embark on your next projects?

00:38:56.010 --> 00:38:57.760
NICOLE GALLAND: I'm a
little superstitious

00:38:57.760 --> 00:39:00.930
about talking about stuff
that hasn't been birthed yet.

00:39:00.930 --> 00:39:02.454
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:39:02.454 --> 00:39:04.120
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah,
I'm the same way,

00:39:04.120 --> 00:39:06.960
so I resort to generalities.

00:39:06.960 --> 00:39:11.370
So both of us are
working on solo books,

00:39:11.370 --> 00:39:15.390
so although we had a
great time collaborating,

00:39:15.390 --> 00:39:18.990
that's an unnatural
state of affairs,

00:39:18.990 --> 00:39:22.170
and we're both
reverting to form.

00:39:22.170 --> 00:39:23.730
So I'm working on one that is--

00:39:27.020 --> 00:39:30.350
technically, you could call
it a follow-on to "Reamde,"

00:39:30.350 --> 00:39:34.070
but it's so different
from "Reamde"

00:39:34.070 --> 00:39:35.990
that it's just going
to confuse everybody

00:39:35.990 --> 00:39:39.650
if I describe it that way.

00:39:39.650 --> 00:39:45.530
So back to more of a
contemporary near term sci-fi

00:39:45.530 --> 00:39:49.149
kind of sensibility.

00:39:49.149 --> 00:39:50.690
NICOLE GALLAND: I'm
writing something

00:39:50.690 --> 00:39:52.960
that requires me to read the
West Tisbury Town Report.

00:40:00.760 --> 00:40:01.610
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:40:01.610 --> 00:40:03.260
I'm wondering,
how much influence

00:40:03.260 --> 00:40:06.080
do you have over the audiobook
versions of your works?

00:40:06.080 --> 00:40:09.975
Do you work with the
narrators, or is this just--

00:40:09.975 --> 00:40:12.890
sometimes I wonder if it's this
third party's interpretation

00:40:12.890 --> 00:40:14.660
of the work that I'm
actually getting.

00:40:14.660 --> 00:40:18.140
NICOLE GALLAND: Normally, it is
a third party interpretation.

00:40:18.140 --> 00:40:21.020
In fact, for "Stepdog,"
a friend of mine who's

00:40:21.020 --> 00:40:24.020
in the industry scolded
me that I was sort

00:40:24.020 --> 00:40:26.870
of trying to indirectly
get to the actor,

00:40:26.870 --> 00:40:30.230
because we happened to
know him a little bit.

00:40:30.230 --> 00:40:33.380
But in this particular
case, that same person

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:35.660
is now very happy
with me, because I

00:40:35.660 --> 00:40:39.350
got her the role of Mel, the
voice that I was just reading.

00:40:39.350 --> 00:40:43.170
She is my college roommate, who
studied linguistics at Harvard,

00:40:43.170 --> 00:40:45.740
and she is now playing
the voice of a person that

00:40:45.740 --> 00:40:47.369
studied linguistics at Harvard.

00:40:47.369 --> 00:40:48.410
She's a voiceover artist.

00:40:48.410 --> 00:40:50.540
I mean I didn't just
pluck her out of nowhere.

00:40:50.540 --> 00:40:54.350
So I got to have control over
that, which was really fun.

00:40:54.350 --> 00:40:56.810
And in this particular
case, there's

00:40:56.810 --> 00:41:00.170
a few funky things
about how Mel writes.

00:41:00.170 --> 00:41:04.530
She's writing, as she says, with
a dip pen in Victorian England.

00:41:04.530 --> 00:41:06.410
So what I did not
include is that there's

00:41:06.410 --> 00:41:09.890
a few places where as she's
writing, she drops an F bomb

00:41:09.890 --> 00:41:12.260
or says something that's
very anachronistic.

00:41:12.260 --> 00:41:14.380
And then she crosses
it out, and then puts

00:41:14.380 --> 00:41:18.519
something that's more Victorian,
because she is clearly

00:41:18.519 --> 00:41:20.560
going to be stuck there
for the rest of her life.

00:41:20.560 --> 00:41:23.090
So she's trying to make
herself think like a Victorian.

00:41:23.090 --> 00:41:26.420
And so she's correcting
herself, and in the audio book,

00:41:26.420 --> 00:41:29.810
the way that they did that was
[INAUDIBLE] would start to say,

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:31.730
"fu--" and then she'd
cut herself off,

00:41:31.730 --> 00:41:34.280
and then they added
a little sound bite

00:41:34.280 --> 00:41:39.530
that was the sound of a
pen scratching out a word.

00:41:39.530 --> 00:41:41.510
So that was-- she
came up with what

00:41:41.510 --> 00:41:43.220
she was going to do
by talking to me,

00:41:43.220 --> 00:41:46.030
and then once they heard her,
they added the scratchy thing.

00:41:46.030 --> 00:41:47.196
NEAL STEPHENSON: Nice, nice.

00:41:47.196 --> 00:41:47.960
Yeah.

00:41:47.960 --> 00:41:49.790
No, it's gotten
really interesting,

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:53.870
because it blew up into
such a big important market

00:41:53.870 --> 00:41:57.640
that a lot of smart
people are getting engaged

00:41:57.640 --> 00:42:01.610
and thinking about how to
make the process better.

00:42:01.610 --> 00:42:05.630
And so it's changed
my style a little bit,

00:42:05.630 --> 00:42:09.350
because I used to put more
diagrams and things that you

00:42:09.350 --> 00:42:11.690
can't read out loud into books.

00:42:11.690 --> 00:42:13.280
And now I don't do that.

00:42:13.280 --> 00:42:16.460
Like footnotes, for
example, are problematic.

00:42:16.460 --> 00:42:19.990
Like some actors have like their
special footnote tone of voice

00:42:19.990 --> 00:42:22.670
that they'll go into
to sort of give you

00:42:22.670 --> 00:42:24.180
a cue that this is a footnote.

00:42:24.180 --> 00:42:27.800
But it's still really
awkward in audio.

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:30.640
And I just heard that--

00:42:30.640 --> 00:42:33.090
this might be
interesting to you--

00:42:33.090 --> 00:42:35.720
I can't remember if it's
Brilliance or Audible,

00:42:35.720 --> 00:42:40.940
but one of the big
audio book companies

00:42:40.940 --> 00:42:46.300
is trying to reach
out to playwrights

00:42:46.300 --> 00:42:50.780
and produce more
original content that

00:42:50.780 --> 00:42:52.672
would be more dramatic.

00:42:52.672 --> 00:42:54.380
NICOLE GALLAND: Well,
that's interesting.

00:42:54.380 --> 00:42:56.171
NEAL STEPHENSON: As
opposed to just reading

00:42:56.171 --> 00:42:57.980
a prose book that's
actually set up

00:42:57.980 --> 00:43:00.240
like what we used
to call a radio play

00:43:00.240 --> 00:43:04.700
and what is now
called an audio drama.

00:43:04.700 --> 00:43:06.710
So it's a huge market,
because there's

00:43:06.710 --> 00:43:12.530
all these people, like long haul
truck drivers or assembly line

00:43:12.530 --> 00:43:16.370
workers, who listen
to audio books

00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:19.290
like eight, 10, 12 hours a day.

00:43:19.290 --> 00:43:24.020
And so they have an insatiable
demand for this stuff.

00:43:24.020 --> 00:43:26.810
And so all kinds of
really interesting things

00:43:26.810 --> 00:43:29.780
are going on in that space,
and it's a cool space to be in.

00:43:29.780 --> 00:43:31.280
NICOLE GALLAND: You
just reminded me

00:43:31.280 --> 00:43:33.530
of something that's only
tangentially related,

00:43:33.530 --> 00:43:34.700
historically.

00:43:34.700 --> 00:43:38.210
In Cuba, the cigar rollers used
to have professional readers

00:43:38.210 --> 00:43:41.750
brought over from Europe to
read them Tolstoy and things

00:43:41.750 --> 00:43:42.880
like that.

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:44.570
So it's a grand old tradition.

00:43:44.570 --> 00:43:45.800
I'm glad it's continuing.

00:43:45.800 --> 00:43:47.810
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah,
the Monte Cristo cigar,

00:43:47.810 --> 00:43:51.770
which is one of the
best, most famous cigars,

00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:54.920
was named that,
because in that room,

00:43:54.920 --> 00:43:57.650
the favorite book of
those cigar rollers

00:43:57.650 --> 00:43:59.650
was "The Count of Monte Cristo."

00:43:59.650 --> 00:44:00.570
Yeah.

00:44:00.570 --> 00:44:01.070
Yeah.

00:44:04.170 --> 00:44:05.980
Anyone?

00:44:05.980 --> 00:44:06.790
OK, all right.

00:44:09.350 --> 00:44:12.170
AUDIENCE: So I assume you
guys enjoy writing books,

00:44:12.170 --> 00:44:14.630
but it's also your job.

00:44:14.630 --> 00:44:16.580
So how does that
kind of play out?

00:44:16.580 --> 00:44:18.920
Is there conflict
at any time in terms

00:44:18.920 --> 00:44:20.960
of like when it ceases
to be enjoyable,

00:44:20.960 --> 00:44:25.049
and it becomes just a job?

00:44:25.049 --> 00:44:26.590
NICOLE GALLAND: I've
had just a jobs,

00:44:26.590 --> 00:44:29.710
and writing is never just a job.

00:44:29.710 --> 00:44:31.690
It's a lot of work sometimes.

00:44:31.690 --> 00:44:33.130
Sometimes it's really fun.

00:44:33.130 --> 00:44:35.120
When I wrote my first
novel, "The Fool's Tale,"

00:44:35.120 --> 00:44:37.420
at a certain point, I went
from having writer's block

00:44:37.420 --> 00:44:38.710
to being completely obsessed.

00:44:38.710 --> 00:44:42.820
And I was writing 17 hours
a day and couldn't stop.

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:45.250
Like the discipline
was to stop doing it

00:44:45.250 --> 00:44:48.970
and do things like eat breakfast
or take a shower or sleep.

00:44:48.970 --> 00:44:51.820
And then there's other times
that it's like pulling teeth,

00:44:51.820 --> 00:44:53.410
but neither of
those two extremes

00:44:53.410 --> 00:44:56.830
are how I've ever felt
about anything that's

00:44:56.830 --> 00:44:59.230
like a job, where you show
up somewhere and have a boss

00:44:59.230 --> 00:45:02.620
and do your job,
and then go home.

00:45:02.620 --> 00:45:06.070
So for me personally,
it's its own thing.

00:45:06.070 --> 00:45:09.970
And even though it varies,
all of its various faces

00:45:09.970 --> 00:45:12.490
are set apart from
any other kind of work

00:45:12.490 --> 00:45:15.340
that I ever did before it.

00:45:15.340 --> 00:45:17.839
You have a different answer,
because you have a different--

00:45:17.839 --> 00:45:20.005
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah, I
figured out a long time ago

00:45:20.005 --> 00:45:21.940
that it's best if I
get up in the morning,

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:24.820
write for a couple of hours,
maybe three hours max,

00:45:24.820 --> 00:45:29.170
and then stop, and do something
else for the rest of the day.

00:45:29.170 --> 00:45:31.780
And by something else, I mean
something that's totally not

00:45:31.780 --> 00:45:35.020
writing, something like doing
geeky things or building

00:45:35.020 --> 00:45:40.420
things, because there's a lot
that happens as a background

00:45:40.420 --> 00:45:41.080
process.

00:45:41.080 --> 00:45:43.710
And you've got to
allow that to happen,

00:45:43.710 --> 00:45:46.750
or I have to allow
that to happen,

00:45:46.750 --> 00:45:50.260
because if I don't, then
when I get up the next day

00:45:50.260 --> 00:45:55.500
and go back to writing,
I don't have anything.

00:45:55.500 --> 00:45:58.840
So I just long ago
figured out I had

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:03.520
to let the mysterious
background process do its thing.

00:46:03.520 --> 00:46:12.430
And then even doing two,
even one hour of work a day

00:46:12.430 --> 00:46:16.570
generates enough material
to produce a book in a year,

00:46:16.570 --> 00:46:18.310
two years easy.

00:46:18.310 --> 00:46:19.820
So it's not a--

00:46:19.820 --> 00:46:23.500
it doesn't slow things
down to take that kind

00:46:23.500 --> 00:46:26.150
of measured paced approach.

00:46:26.150 --> 00:46:29.165
But there is this weird
thing that it's like--

00:46:29.165 --> 00:46:30.790
you know, we used to
call it dieseling,

00:46:30.790 --> 00:46:33.310
where you shut your
car off, but the engine

00:46:33.310 --> 00:46:36.070
keeps running for
a little while.

00:46:36.070 --> 00:46:37.070
That happens to me.

00:46:37.070 --> 00:46:40.810
So when I stop, I have to
carry my phone around with me

00:46:40.810 --> 00:46:45.850
and do voice memos
for about 15 minutes,

00:46:45.850 --> 00:46:52.750
because I'll get like
lines of dialogue or ideas

00:46:52.750 --> 00:46:57.080
that are kind of
dieseling in my head.

00:46:57.080 --> 00:47:01.690
It's usually good stuff, and
so I'll make a record of those.

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:05.760
And then that's where
I start the next day.

00:47:05.760 --> 00:47:07.250
So.

