out how to phrase it.

00:47:13.780 --> 00:47:15.790
This one's
specifically for Neal.

00:47:15.790 --> 00:47:18.740
You've written a lot of
pretty well-known books

00:47:18.740 --> 00:47:21.110
and have a lot of fans.

00:47:21.110 --> 00:47:23.140
And I'm wondering out
of all those books,

00:47:23.140 --> 00:47:26.819
which ones do you think has
produced the most rabid fans?

00:47:26.819 --> 00:47:28.360
NEAL STEPHENSON:
The most rabid fans?

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:30.250
AUDIENCE: Yeah, you know,
which books are most--

00:47:30.250 --> 00:47:31.810
I don't want to say
inspiring, but--

00:47:37.029 --> 00:47:39.320
NEAL STEPHENSON: There's
different kinds of rabid fans.

00:47:39.320 --> 00:47:43.280
There's like a
taxonomy of rabid fans.

00:47:43.280 --> 00:47:48.670
So I think it seems to me
that among female readers,

00:47:48.670 --> 00:47:50.590
"Diamond Age" and
"Snow Crash" are

00:47:50.590 --> 00:47:56.170
both super popular, maybe
"Diamond Age" a little more so.

00:47:56.170 --> 00:48:00.310
And then "Cryptonomicon"
is really popular.

00:48:00.310 --> 00:48:05.550
It's just it's always a
different rabid fan kind of.

00:48:05.550 --> 00:48:06.804
What's that?

00:48:06.804 --> 00:48:07.720
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:08.636
NEAL STEPHENSON: Yeah.

00:48:08.636 --> 00:48:14.590
Yeah, and so for example, when
I published "Quicksilver,"

00:48:14.590 --> 00:48:20.080
which is my first kind of
straight up historical novel,

00:48:20.080 --> 00:48:20.620
I went.

00:48:20.620 --> 00:48:26.070
I did a tour in the UK for that,
and some guy approached me,

00:48:26.070 --> 00:48:29.920
a silver-haired guy
walked up and said hello.

00:48:29.920 --> 00:48:33.730
And he had become
a fan of that book,

00:48:33.730 --> 00:48:39.400
but he had no idea I had
written anything else.

00:48:39.400 --> 00:48:42.565
So that's just kind of
how that market works

00:48:42.565 --> 00:48:43.790
for whatever reason.

00:48:47.164 --> 00:48:48.580
SPEAKER: We have
a couple minutes,

00:48:48.580 --> 00:48:49.840
so I'm going to ask
a follow-up to that,

00:48:49.840 --> 00:48:51.760
which is, Nicole,
you're mostly known

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:54.530
for writing historical fiction.

00:48:54.530 --> 00:48:56.530
So this is a little
out of genre.

00:48:56.530 --> 00:48:59.980
Do you find that a lot of your
fans are excited for this book

00:48:59.980 --> 00:49:03.100
or excited for you to do more
stuff like this that's kind

00:49:03.100 --> 00:49:05.016
of comedic or more
sci-fi-ey, or--

00:49:05.016 --> 00:49:06.140
NICOLE GALLAND: I think so.

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:08.770
Something that I've been
trying to come to terms with

00:49:08.770 --> 00:49:12.610
is the fact that I think
I'm a little funnier than I

00:49:12.610 --> 00:49:13.270
think I am.

00:49:16.150 --> 00:49:19.240
I don't think of myself
as trying to write funny,

00:49:19.240 --> 00:49:22.240
but that seems to be a lot of
the feedback that I'm getting

00:49:22.240 --> 00:49:24.490
is that's part of what
people like about my writing.

00:49:24.490 --> 00:49:28.030
This is not as out of genre as
my last book, which I think we

00:49:28.030 --> 00:49:29.770
were talking about this before.

00:49:29.770 --> 00:49:31.960
I wrote one contemporary
romantic comedy.

00:49:31.960 --> 00:49:35.080
It's the last book that I
wrote, and this actually

00:49:35.080 --> 00:49:41.080
feels like a return to form,
because for instance, we

00:49:41.080 --> 00:49:44.920
needed medieval warfare
for a section of this book.

00:49:44.920 --> 00:49:46.780
And so we chose
the Fourth Crusade,

00:49:46.780 --> 00:49:50.380
because I wrote a
novel called "Crossed:

00:49:50.380 --> 00:49:52.120
A Tale of the Fourth Crusade."

00:49:52.120 --> 00:49:53.770
So we were drawing--

00:49:53.770 --> 00:49:58.540
I actually got to return to a
lot of my stuff in doing this.

00:49:58.540 --> 00:50:00.460
"Stepdog" was the
one that just--

00:50:00.460 --> 00:50:05.020
even my editor said, well,
that came out of nowhere.

00:50:05.020 --> 00:50:08.380
So this was sort of like
a fun, playful return

00:50:08.380 --> 00:50:10.510
to familiar
material, but getting

00:50:10.510 --> 00:50:11.750
to do it in a whole new way.

00:50:11.750 --> 00:50:13.820
And that was delightful.

00:50:13.820 --> 00:50:18.314
I love trying new things,
and this was just delightful.

00:50:18.314 --> 00:50:20.230
SPEAKER: Do you have you
Easter egg characters

00:50:20.230 --> 00:50:21.946
from your previous
Fourth Crusade book?

00:50:24.346 --> 00:50:25.720
NICOLE GALLAND:
I don't think so.

